x4freetext: FRM research reactor with 4 MW thermal power.
Converter facility with an U-235 converter
plate operating at a thermal power of about 10 kw,
delivering an intense beam of nondegraded fission
radiation. 5 m from the source the beam was shaped to
.143 KeV neutrons were produced with a 124.5 cm long
silicon filter. The mean energy width was 20 KeV.
.Neutrons of mean energy 1.3 MeV were produced with a
combination of 17.5 cm lead, 2 cm polyethylene and
spectrum had a 80 percent width from 0.55 to 3 MeV.
.Neutrons of mean energy 2.1 MeV were produced with a
combination of 10 cm lead, 7 cm polyethylene and
spectrum had a 80 percent width from 1 to 5 MeV.
The detector was placed at a distance of 9 m from
the source, where the beam was collimated to a dia-
meter of 1.5 cm. The detector consisted of a poly-
ethylene sheet, 29.5 by 3 by 0.5 cm, inclined by 10
degrees in the beam line and of two thermal neutron
counters (enriched BF3 counters) on both sides of the
sheet. This arrangement was placed in the middle of a
polyethylene block with a wall thickness of 8 cm. The
block was completely covered with cadmium and located
inside a water container (65 by 65 by 65 cm).
.The samples used were chemically pure (g.T. 99.9 per-
cent) and had different thicknesses. The physical and
